<HEAD>West Germany Has Long History Of Spy Scandals</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Spy Ring, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist spies have been operating in
West Germany since its founding in 1949. Here are some of the more
recent spy cases, as well as some of the more notorious ones:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 28, 1988 _ West German federal law authorities announce
the arrest of 10 people who are accused of working for the Soviet
KGB. Chief Federal Prosecutor Kurt Rebmann said the roundup marked
``an important penetration of the KGB spy network.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 31, 1987 _ Margaret Hoeke, a secretary for five West German
presidents, is sentenced to eight years in prison after admitting
she gave state secrets to a KGB agent because she was lonely and
loved him. The information she handed over included sensitive
correspondence between U.S. President Reagan and West German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   1985 _ Hans Joachim Tiedge, head of a West German
counterintelligence unit responsible for catching East German
spies, defects to East Germany.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   1976 _ Lothar-Erwin Lutze and his wife Renate are among 16
people arrested in an espionage crackdown. The Lutzes had passed
NATO documents to East Germany since the 1960s. Then-Defense
Minister Georg Leber resigns over the scandal. The Lutzes are later
released to East Germany in a spy swap.
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   1974 _ Guenter Guillaume, a top aide to then-Chancellor Willy
Brandt, is exposed as an East German agent. The resulting scandal
forces Brandt to resign. Guillaume gets a 13-year prison sentence
but is released to East Germany in an East-West spy exchange six
years later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
